# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: board-of-directors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:board-of-directors/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] An **account manager** (**AM**) is a person who works for a company and is responsible for the management of sales and relationships with particular customers.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] An account manager maintains the company's existing relationships with a client or group of clients, so that they will continue using the company for business.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Account managers do not manage the daily running of the account.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] They manage the relationship with the client of the account(s) they are assigned to.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Generally, a client will remain with one account manager throughout the account's duration.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Account managers serve as the interface between customer service and the sales team in a company.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] They are assigned a company's existing client accounts.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The purpose of being assigned particular clients is to create long term client relationships.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The account manager serves to understand the customer's demands, plan how to meet these demands, and generate sales for the company as a result.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The responsibilities of account managers can vary depending on the industry they work in, size of the company and nature of the business.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Each customer account can vary in demands and an account manager may work with brand managers for one account and a media department for another.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Account managers usually report directly to the account director or agency director of the activity and status of accounts and transactions.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] An account manager may also manage a single account or a variety of accounts depending on the requirement of the company.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Manage and solve conflicts with clients The Account Manager is expected to have specific information regarding the daily operations of the company and keep the Client updated.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] There are situations in which an account manager, for example in advertising firms, is responsible for more than one account and therefore looks after multiple clients.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] When account locations do not overlap the account manager can be placed at the divisional, district, or territory level.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] When a sales team has a senior sales manager, the account manager coordinates sales accounts from other departments or specialties.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] In this scenario, the sales team will work under the direct supervision of influencers and deciders instead of with a buyer.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Global account managers and national account managers may work together in a hierarchical or matrix structure.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The trend is to move responsibility for the major key accounts to the global level.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] A key account manager (KAM) is assigned to a company headquarters to oversee the account team assigned to a particular account.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Key account management includes sales but also includes planning and managing the full relationship between a business and its most important customers.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] An account manager who works in this role will engage in a variety of tasks including project management, coordination, strategic planning, relationship management, negotiation, leadership and innovative development of opportunities, and keeping record of transactions of sale and purchase goods.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The tasks may include working with product design and application, logistics, sales support, and marketing.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] The basic assumption for a key account management model is the correct classification of the key accounts.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] A basic model often used from 1950 to 1970 was the classification model of Webster.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] This model has been adapted by Milman and Wilson into a two-dimensional model and was paramount from 1970 to 1990.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Bensaou has tested this model empirically by his research of carmakers in the United States and Japan and made revisions.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] De Blick synthesized the adaptations into the 4S-model, a key account classification model.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] By the late 1990s, key account management spread to most B2B (business-to-business) models.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Account managers can work for small or large companies either corporate, financial, retail, or government for instance.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Any company with a specific set of clients they conduct business with, can employ an account manager.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Account managers usually work in an office setting and can work more than 40 hours weekly.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Travel is usually included in the job description.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] National or global account managers will very likely experience extra travel.
[src:board-of-directors/account-manager] Although personality and an aptitude for sales is key, a degree in business, marketing, or related field is typically required and depending on the nature of the account, a background in marketing or media studies may be preferred.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] An **account of profits** (sometimes referred to as an **accounting for profits** or simply an **accounting**) is a type of equitable remedy most commonly used in cases of breach of fiduciary duty.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] It is an action taken against a defendant to recover the profits taken as a result of the breach of duty, in order to prevent unjust enrichment.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] In conducting an account of profits, the plaintiff is treated as if they were conducting the business of the defendant, and made those profits which were attributable to the defendant's wrongful actions.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] This can be rather complex in practice, because the defendant's accounting records must be examined (sometimes by a forensic accountant) to determine what portion of his gross profits were derived to the wrongful act in question.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] As a result, mathematical exactness is not called for and reasonable approximation is acceptable.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] Historically an account was not an equitable remedy, but was an action at common law, and is therefore technically an instrument of law, though it arose at a time before the distinction between law and equity was marked.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] Co-owners in concurrent estates also have the right to an accounting of profits, in order to properly apportion income from the use or leasing of the property.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] The remedy is also available against strangers to a trust who "dishonestly assist" an express trustee in a breach of the trustee's fiduciary duty.
[src:board-of-directors/account-of-profits] To account for the entire business and its profits, due allowance being made for the time, energy, skill and financial contribution of the fiduciary (the approach in *Boardman v Phipps*).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting can be divided into several fields including financial accounting, management accounting, tax accounting and cost accounting.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Financial accounting focuses on the reporting of an organization's financial information, including the preparation of financial statements, to the external users of the information, such as investors, regulators and suppliers.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Management accounting focuses on the measurement, analysis and reporting of information for internal use by management to enhance business operations.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The recording of financial transactions, so that summaries of the financials may be presented in financial reports, is known as bookkeeping, of which double-entry bookkeeping is the most common system.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting information systems are designed to support accounting functions and related activities.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting has existed in various forms and levels of sophistication throughout human history.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The double-entry accounting system in use today was developed in medieval Europe, particularly in Venice, and is usually attributed to the Italian mathematician and Franciscan friar Luca Pacioli.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Today, accounting is facilitated by accounting organizations such as standard-setters, accounting firms and professional bodies.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Financial statements are usually audited by accounting firms, and are prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] GAAP is set by various standard-setting organizations such as the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) in the United States and the Financial Reporting Council in the United Kingdom.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] As of 2012, "all major economies" have plans to converge towards or adopt the International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting is thousands of years old and can be traced to ancient civilizations.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] One early development of accounting dates back to ancient Mesopotamia and is closely related to developments in writing, counting and money; there is also evidence of early forms of bookkeeping in ancient Iran, and early auditing systems by the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] By the time of Emperor Augustus, the Roman government had access to detailed financial information.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The spread of the use of Arabic numerals, instead of the Roman numbers historically used in Europe, increased efficiency of accounting procedures among Mediterranean merchants, who further refined accounting in medieval Europe.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] With the development of joint-stock companies, accounting split into financial accounting and management accounting.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The first published work on a double-entry bookkeeping system was the *Summa de arithmetica*, published in Italy in 1494 by Luca Pacioli (the "Father of Accounting").
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting began to transition into an organized profession in the 19th century, with local professional bodies in England merging to form the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales in 1880.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Both the words "accounting" and "accountancy" were in use in Great Britain by the mid-1800s and are derived from the words *accompting* and *accountantship* used in the 18th century.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In Middle English (used roughly between the 12th and the late 15th century), the verb "to account" had the form *accounten*, which was derived from the Old French word *aconter*, which is in turn related to the Vulgar Latin word *computare*, meaning "to reckon".
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The base of *computare* is *putare*, which "variously meant to prune, to purify, to correct an account, hence, to count or calculate, as well as to think".
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The word "accountant" is derived from the French word *compter*, which is also derived from the Italian and Latin word *computare*.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The word was formerly written in English as "accomptant", but in process of time the word, which was always pronounced by dropping the "p", became gradually changed both in pronunciation and in orthography to its present form.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting has several subfields or subject areas, including financial accounting, management accounting, auditing, taxation and accounting information systems.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Financial accounting focuses on the reporting of an organization's financial information to external users of the information, such as investors, potential investors and creditors.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] It calculates and records business transactions and prepares financial statements for the external users in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] GAAP, in turn, arises from the wide agreement between accounting theory and practice, and changes over time to meet the needs of decision-makers.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Financial accounting produces past-oriented reports—for example financial statements are often published six to ten months after the end of the accounting period—on an annual or quarterly basis, generally about the organization as a whole.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Management accounting focuses on the measurement, analysis and reporting of information that can help managers in making decisions to fulfill the goals of an organization.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In management accounting, internal measures and reports are based on cost–benefit analysis, and are not required to follow the generally accepted accounting principle (GAAP).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In 2014 CIMA created the Global Management Accounting Principles (GMAPs).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The result of research from across 20 countries in five continents, the principles aim to guide best practice in the discipline.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Management accounting produces past-oriented reports with time spans that vary widely, but it also encompasses future-oriented reports such as budgets.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Management accounting reports often include financial and non financial information, and may, for example, focus on specific products and departments.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Intercompany accounting focuses on the measurement, analysis and reporting of information between separate entities that are related, such as a parent company and its subsidiary companies.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Intercompany accounting concerns record keeping of transactions between companies that have common ownership such as a parent company and a partially or wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Intercompany transactions are also recorded in accounting when business is transacted between companies with a common parent company (subsidiaries).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Auditing is the verification of assertions made by others regarding a payoff, and in the context of accounting it is the "unbiased examination and evaluation of the financial statements of an organization".
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Audit is a professional service that is systematic and conventional.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] An audit of financial statements aims to express or disclaim an independent opinion on the financial statements.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The auditor expresses an independent opinion on the fairness with which the financial statements presents the financial position, results of operations, and cash flows of an entity, in accordance with the generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) and "in all material respects".
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] An auditor is also required to identify circumstances in which the generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) have not been consistently observed.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] An accounting information system is a part of an organization's information system used for processing accounting data.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Many corporations use artificial intelligence-based information systems.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The banking and finance industry uses AI in fraud detection.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The retail industry uses AI for customer services.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] AI is also used in the cybersecurity industry.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] It involves computer hardware and software systems using statistics and modeling.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Many accounting practices have been simplified with the help of accounting computer-based software.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] An enterprise resource planning (ERP) system is commonly used for a large organisation and it provides a comprehensive, centralized, integrated source of information that companies can use to manage all major business processes, from purchasing to manufacturing to human resources.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] These systems can be cloud based and available on demand via application or browser, or available as software installed on specific computers or local servers, often referred to as on-premise.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Tax accounting in the United States concentrates on the preparation, analysis and presentation of tax payments and tax returns.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The U.S. tax system requires the use of specialised accounting principles for tax purposes which can differ from the generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) for financial reporting.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] U.S. tax law covers three basic forms of business ownership: partnership, corporation, and disregarded entity.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Corporate and personal income are taxed at different rates, both varying according to income levels and including varying marginal rates (taxed on each additional dollar of income) and average rates (set as a percentage of overall income).
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Forensic accounting is a specialty practice area of accounting that describes engagements that result from actual or anticipated disputes or litigation.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] "Forensic" means "suitable for use in a court of law", and it is to that standard and potential outcome that forensic accountants generally have to work.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Political campaign accounting deals with the development and implementation of financial systems and the accounting of financial transactions in compliance with laws governing political campaign operations.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] This branch of accounting was first formally introduced in the March 1976 issue of *The Journal of Accountancy*.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Many of these professional bodies offer education and training including qualification and administration for various accounting designations, such as certified public accountant (AICPA) and chartered accountant.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Depending on its size, a company may be legally required to have their financial statements audited by a qualified auditor, and audits are usually carried out by accounting firms.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting firms grew in the United States and Europe in the late nineteenth and early twentieth century, and through several mergers there were large international accounting firms by the mid-twentieth century.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Further large mergers in the late twentieth century led to the dominance of the auditing market by the "Big Five" accounting firms: Arthur Andersen, Deloitte, Ernst & Young, KPMG and PricewaterhouseCoopers.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The demise of Arthur Andersen following the Enron scandal reduced the Big Five to the Big Four.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) are accounting standards issued by national regulatory bodies.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In addition, the International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) issues the International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS) implemented by 147 countries.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Standards for international audit and assurance, ethics, education, and public sector accounting are all set by independent standard settings boards supported by IFAC.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Organizations in individual countries may issue accounting standards unique to the countries.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] For example, in Australia, the Australian Accounting Standards Board manages the issuance of the accounting standards in line with IFRS.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In the United States the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issues the Statements of Financial Accounting Standards, which form the basis of US GAAP, and in the United Kingdom the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) sets accounting standards.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] However, as of 2012 "all major economies" have plans to converge towards or adopt the IFRS.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] A bachelor's degree or a master's degree in accounting or a related field is required for most accountant and auditor job positions, and some employers prefer applicants with advanced qualifications.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] A degree in accounting may also be required for, or may be used to fulfill the requirements for, membership to professional accounting bodies.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] For example, the education during an accounting degree can be used to fulfill the American Institute of CPA's (AICPA) 150 semester hour requirement, and associate membership with the Certified Public Accountants Association of the UK is available after gaining a degree in finance or accounting.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] A doctorate is required in order to pursue a career in accounting academia, for example, to work as a university professor in accounting.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) and the Doctor of Business Administration (DBA) are the most popular degrees.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The PhD is the most common degree for those wishing to pursue a career in academia, while DBA programs generally focus on equipping business executives for business or public careers requiring research skills and qualifications.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Professional accounting qualifications include the chartered accountant designations and other qualifications including certificates and diplomas.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In Scotland, chartered accountants of ICAS undergo Continuous Professional Development and abide by the ICAS code of ethics.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In England and Wales, chartered accountants of the ICAEW undergo annual training, and are bound by the ICAEW's code of ethics and subject to its disciplinary procedures.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In the United States, the requirements for joining the AICPA as a Certified Public Accountant are set by the Board of Accountancy of each state, and members agree to abide by the AICPA's Code of Professional Conduct and Bylaws.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The ACCA is the largest global accountancy body with over 320,000 members, and the organisation provides an 'IFRS stream' and a 'UK stream'.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Students must pass a total of 14 exams, which are arranged across three levels.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting research is research in the effects of economic events on the process of accounting, the effects of reported information on economic events, and the roles of accounting in organizations and society.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] It encompasses a broad range of research areas including financial accounting, management accounting, auditing and taxation.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting research is carried out both by academic researchers and practicing accountants.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Empirical studies document that leading accounting journals publish in total fewer research articles than comparable journals in economics and other business disciplines, and consequently, accounting scholars are relatively less successful in academic publishing than their business school peers.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Due to different publication rates between accounting and other business disciplines, a recent study based on academic author rankings concludes that the competitive value of a single publication in a top-ranked journal is highest in accounting and lowest in marketing.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The year 2001 witnessed a series of financial information frauds involving Enron, auditing firm Arthur Andersen, the telecommunications company WorldCom, Qwest and Sunbeam, among other well-known corporations.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] These problems highlighted the need to review the effectiveness of accounting standards, auditing regulations and corporate governance principles.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In some cases, management manipulated the figures shown in financial reports to indicate a better economic performance.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In others, tax and regulatory incentives encouraged over-leveraging of companies and decisions to bear extraordinary and unjustified risk.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] In addition to being the largest bankruptcy reorganization in American history, the Enron scandal undoubtedly is the biggest audit failure causing the dissolution of Arthur Andersen, which at the time was one of the five largest accounting firms in the world.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] After a series of revelations involving irregular accounting procedures conducted throughout the 1990s, Enron filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in December 2001.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] One consequence of these events was the passage of the Sarbanes–Oxley Act in the United States in 2002, as a result of the first admissions of fraudulent behavior made by Enron.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The act significantly raises criminal penalties for securities fraud, for destroying, altering or fabricating records in federal investigations or any scheme or attempt to defraud shareholders.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Accounting fraud is an intentional misstatement or omission in the accounting records by management or employees which involves the use of deception.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] It is a criminal act and a breach of civil tort.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] It may involve collusion with third parties.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] An accounting error is an unintentional misstatement or omission in the accounting records, for example misinterpretation of facts, mistakes in processing data, or oversights leading to incorrect estimates.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] Acts leading to accounting errors are not criminal but may breach civil law, for example, the tort of negligence.
[src:board-of-directors/accounting] The primary responsibility for the prevention and detection of fraud and errors rests with the entity's management.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] In management, an **action item** is a documented event, task, activity, or action that needs to take place.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Action items are discrete units that can be handled by a single person.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Action items are usually created during a discussion by a group of people who are meeting about one or more topics, and during the discussion, it is discovered that some kind of action is needed.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] The act required is then documented as an action item and is typically assigned to someone, usually a member of the group.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] The person to whom the action is assigned is then obligated to perform the action and report back to the group on the results.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Action items are usually documented in the meeting minutes and are recorded in the task list of the group.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] As people complete action items, the items are documented as being completed and the item is removed from the list of outstanding action items.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] A usual format for an action item is to record an action item number, the date when the action item is identified or created, the name of the person to whom the action is assigned, a title description of the action, a more detailed description of the action and its outcomes, and its deliverables.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] An action item can be considered a more general form of various types of action/issue/defect tracking methods.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] For instance, a bug report is a form of an action item, as is a service report created by a service company to track a problem reported by a customer or an RMA number.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Follow up in a consistent and timely manner with the responsible individual(s) to track their progress and drive the action item to resolution.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] It is important to understand the distinction here that we track to resolution and not to completion.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] While it is the goal to have every action item completed, there are numerous scenarios in which the action item may no longer be relevant or completion may not be possible.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] There are a number of software applications for tracking action items or service reports.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] These applications are used within software development organizations as well as in customer support functions.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Because these software applications facilitate group communication, they are often referred to as Collaborative software or groupware.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Various such software are available in the market.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] They are known to increase the productivity of Managers.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] Many information technology support groups use some kind of service report software so that when a trouble report is called in, the person answering the telephone will create a trouble ticket to track the issue.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] The trouble ticket is assigned to a member of the IT services organization, who then visits the person who has reported a problem and resolves the problem.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] The IT services person will then close out the trouble ticket, indicating the issue has been resolved.
[src:board-of-directors/action-item] The concept was parodied in 2000 by Neil McAllister in a widely circulated "superhero" comic strip.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An **advisory board** is a body that provides non-binding strategic advice to the management of a corporation, organization, or foundation.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The informal nature of an advisory board gives greater flexibility in structure and management compared to the board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Unlike the board of directors, the advisory board does not have authority to vote on corporate matters or bear legal fiduciary responsibilities.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Many new or small businesses choose to have advisory boards in order to benefit from the knowledge of others, without the expense or formality of the board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The function of an advisory board is to offer assistance to enterprises with anything from marketing to managing human resources to influencing the direction of regulators.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory boards are composed of accomplished experts offering innovative advice and dynamic perspectives.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Meeting quarterly or biannually, boards can provide strategic direction, guide quality improvement, and assess program effectiveness.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Entrepreneurs, especially from startup companies or small business may not want to dilute their control of their business by establishing a board of directors with formal responsibilities and authorities.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Thus, an advisory board may be a more suitable solution to entrepreneurs who want access to high-quality advice and network in the industry.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board, as an external group, could also provide non-biased information and advice to entrepreneurs.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory boards can be implemented in various different areas, including science, medicine, technology, editorial policy, citizen participation, and other topics.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The Advisory Board Sector has grown by 52% since 2019 according to the State of the Market Global Report 2021.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The main reason to create an advisory board is to seek expertise outside of the company.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board members should provide the company with knowledge, understanding and strategic thinking of the industry or management of the company.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Companies should seek advisory board members whose qualities complement the existing board of directors and not mask gaps in knowledge or skill in the main board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An advisory board strengthens the existing board, but does not interfere with authorities of the existing board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] There are two key questions to be asked when creating and operating an advisory board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The first question is who is trying to achieve what from an advisory board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The second question is how the business of the board should be conducted.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The following issues need to be addressed.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The type of advisory board members should be determined by the nature of what is sought and expected from them by the enterprise.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board members should have distinctive knowledge on different aspects of business such as marketing, product development, and sales techniques that are of use to the directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A lack of definition in “what is sought from the advisory board” or “what sort of advice is to be sought” would lead to a disorganized board, which eventually could lead to an advisory board that provide less value per dollar or hour invested than a well-mandated one.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Eventually, it could result in a waste of resources and time for the enterprise and the advisory board members.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The advisory board must determine what the focus of the committee is, whether it is a broad focus or a narrow one on a specific product feature.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Individuals in an advisory board should share a common goal or similar interests.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Size of an advisory board influences the efficiency of delivering ongoing information and effectiveness of organizing board meetings.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A large advisory board may result in managerial issues.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Therefore, it is recommended that an advisory board begin with the advisory board leader, and grow from a fairly small size to its ultimate number.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Group dynamics suggests the maximum size for an advisory board is eight members, which takes into account the need for enterprise people and other facilitators at meetings.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Some advisory board's mandate may require more significant representation of a specific and large number of constituencies.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The functioning of an advisory board is affected significantly by how effectively the group's activities are organized and directed.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A fixed meeting should be held regularly (monthly, annually or other) and advisory board members must be well informed of the purpose and background information of the meeting in order for them to provide valuable advice.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A corollary should be provided to advisory board members, which should be of an appropriate length, organized, comprehensible and informative.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] While it should be concise, it should provide enough details to provide advisory board members a suitable foundation for them to advise on the business.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Confidentiality of the information discussed in the meeting should be considered.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A skilled facilitator, administrator or corporate secretary is required to organize schedules of advisory board meetings and meeting materials.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The facilitator or chair of the board should be committed and aware of time management for the meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An agenda could improve the organization and time management for the meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board members can be appointed to specific terms i.e. one, two or three years ensuring them to actively commit to the company and prevent them from getting too comfortable with their positions.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Term of membership is also important when it comes to expansion of the board; term of membership ensures that the size of the advisory board remains efficient and manageable.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board members serve an enterprise for a range of reasons, from personal loyalty to direct compensation.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Multinational companies have local companies running their business in a particular foreign jurisdiction for lower costs e.g. tax, price of raw materials, and organizational benefits.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] However, giving authority to an outside group of directors in the local company may increase risks and instability of the multinational corporation.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Since an advisory board can operate in a different location, with different cultural and business norms, in a different language, multinational companies may choose to have an advisory board instead of a localized board of directors in order to avoid loss of control.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An advisory board can provide accountability to keep the organization on track, as staff are expected to report on progress.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Companies may choose to have an advisory board before they have a board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The development of an effective board of directors requires a group of individuals with good chemistry and has the combination of appropriate skills to propel the business.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Having an advisory board allows companies to assess the commitments and capabilities of each individual and observe the chemistry between them before appointing them to a board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A large board of directors may grow to an unmanageable size where organizational complexity and communication breakdown may occur, leading to ineffective and inefficient function of the board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A smaller advisory board, without the complexity of authority involved in a board of directors, may work more effectively compared to a board of directors that grows in size as the corporation grows.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The complexity and speed of enterprises often make it difficult to seek advice on any particular topic.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Enterprises may also find building trust in any person or group to provide on-going and meaningful guidance difficult.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An advisory board can then provide the degree of consistency, longevity and background knowledge as advisory board members provide reliable advice on particular issues.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Advisory board members may receive compensation for committing to their positions.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] This gives incentives to advisory board members to provide quality advice and ensure that a request for assistance is taken formally.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Executives can express partially defined or a tentative view to an advisory board since an advisory board's sole purpose is to provide advice.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] This allows them to “test-drive options” before they face the board of directors which demands definitive and assertive business decisions.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] The board of directors assesses the CEO and establishes his or her compensation.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] While an advisory board may induce change in the company for the benefits of the company, a board of directors inducing change in the company could suggest a lack of confidence in the senior management team.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] This imposes great pressure on senior executives and could become a barrier for senior executives to express their issues and seek advice from the board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Thus, an advisory board could be a 'safe harbor' for senior executives to seek advice and test business options.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Directors and Assistant Directors are still required to bring any changes to policy or financial matters to the board for direction.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] No directors or assistant directors should make any changes without board approval.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An enterprise may need advice on a particular aspect of its business (such as marketing, product direction, customer service or contact network expansion).
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] While board of directors need to take into account all aspects and go through a series of administrative proceedings, e.g. formal approval and/or ratification, an advisory board can focus directly on a particular issue and give advice.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] An advisory board deals with a more narrow range of issues and meet less often than a board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] There is less commitment for advisory board members compared to directors on the board.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] This is reflected in the lower compensation advisory board members receive as compared to those on the board of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Nevertheless, the compensation for advisory board members depends on various factors, including return of investments, time, organization and cost.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] A board of directors is exposed to a variety of legislated liabilities, fiduciary and other duties.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Responsibilities include unpaid wages, unpaid taxes, environmental damage, etc.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] By subjecting directors to such liabilities and fiduciary, directors are forced to make decisions and establish policies in a way that minimizes risks.
[src:board-of-directors/advisory-board] Whereas, an advisory board is not subjected to fiduciary duties or liabilities and therefore could influence the enterprise by providing risky advice.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] It may be referred to as the equal relationship between a principal and an agent whereby the principal, expressly or implicitly, authorizes the agent to work under their control and on their behalf.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The agent is, thus, required to negotiate on behalf of the principal or bring them and third parties into a contractual relationship.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The reciprocal rights and liabilities between a principal and an agent reflect commercial and legal realities.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] A business owner often relies on an employee or another person to conduct a business.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In the case of a corporation, since a corporation can only act through natural person agents, the principal is bound by the contract entered into by the agent, so long as the agent performs within the scope of the agency.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] A third party may rely in good faith on the representation by a person who identifies himself as an agent for another.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] It is not always cost effective to check whether someone who is represented as having the authority to act for another actually has such authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If it is subsequently found that the alleged agent was acting without necessary authority, the agent will generally be held liable.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The role of an agent and scope of their authority affect how the agent is described.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Special agents are authorized to perform either a specific transaction or task.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent who acts within the scope of authority conferred by their principal binds the principal in the obligations they create against third parties.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] There are essentially three kinds of authority recognized in the law: actual authority (whether express or implied), apparent authority, and ratified authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Either the principal may have expressly conferred authority on the agent, or authority may be implied.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Authority arises by consensual agreement, and whether it exists is a question of fact.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent, as a general rule, is only entitled to indemnity from the principal if they have acted within the scope of their actual authority, and if they act outside of that authority they may be in breach of contract, and liable to a third party for breach of the implied warranty of authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Express actual authority means an agent has been expressly told they may act on behalf of a principal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Implied actual authority, also called "usual authority", is authority an agent has by virtue of being reasonably necessary to carry out his express authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] As such, it can be inferred by virtue of a position held by an agent.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] For example, partners have authority to bind the other partners in the firm, their liability being joint and several, and in a corporation, all executives and senior employees with decision-making authority by virtue of their position have authority to bind the corporation.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Other forms of implied actual authority include customary authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This is where customs of a trade imply the agent to have certain powers.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In wool buying industries it is customary for traders to purchase in their own names.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Also incidental authority, where an agent is supposed to have any authority to complete other tasks which are necessary and incidental to completing the express actual authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Apparent authority (also called "ostensible authority") exists where the principal's words or conduct would lead a reasonable person in the third party's position to believe that the agent was authorized to act, even if the principal and the purported agent had never discussed such a relationship.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] For example, where one person appoints a person to a position which carries with it agency-like powers, those who know of the appointment are entitled to assume that there is apparent authority to do the things ordinarily entrusted to one occupying such a position.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If a principal creates the impression that an agent is authorized but there is no actual authority, third parties are protected so long as they have acted reasonably.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This is sometimes termed "agency by estoppel" or the "doctrine of holding out", where the principal will be estopped from denying the grant of authority if third parties have changed their positions to their detriment in reliance on the representations made.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In the case of *Watteau v Fenwick*, Lord Coleridge CJ on the Queen's Bench concurred with an opinion by Wills J that a third party could hold personally liable a principal who he did not know about when he sold cigars to an agent that was acting outside of its authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] It is sometimes referred to as "usual authority" (though not in the sense used by Lord Denning MR in *Hely-Hutchinson*, where it is synonymous with "implied actual authority").
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] It has been explained as a form of apparent authority, or "inherent agency power".
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Authority by virtue of a position held to deter fraud and other harms that may befall individuals dealing with agents, there is a concept of Inherent Agency power, which is power derived solely by virtue of the agency relation.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Even if the agent does act without authority, the principal may ratify the transaction and accept liability on the transactions as negotiated.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If the agent has actual or apparent authority, the agent will not be liable for acts performed within the scope of such authority, as long as the relationship of the agency and the identity of the principal have been disclosed.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] When the agency is undisclosed or partially disclosed, however, both the agent and the principal are liable.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Where the principal is not bound because the agent has no actual or apparent authority, the purported agent is liable to the third party for breach of the implied warranty of authority.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If the agent has acted without actual authority, but the principal is nevertheless bound because the agent had apparent authority, the agent is liable to indemnify the principal for any resulting loss or damage.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If the agent has acted within the scope of the actual authority given, the principal must indemnify the agent for payments made during the course of the relationship whether the expenditure was expressly authorized or merely necessary in promoting the principal's business.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent owes the principal a number of duties.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent must not accept any new obligations that are inconsistent with the duties owed to the principal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent can represent the interests of more than one principal, conflicting or potentially conflicting, only after full disclosure and consent of the principal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An agent must not usurp an opportunity from the principal by taking it for himself or passing it on to a third party.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In return, the principal must make a full disclosure of all information relevant to the transactions that the agent is authorized to negotiate.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The internal agency relationship may be dissolved by agreement.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] By discharge of the contractual agency obligations.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The principal also cannot revoke the agent's authority after it has been partly exercised, so as to bind the principal (s.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] 204), though he can always do so, before such authority has been so exercised (s.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] 205, if the agency is for a fixed period, the principal cannot terminate the agency before the time expired, except for sufficient cause.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] If he does, he is liable to compensate the agent for the loss caused to him thereby.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The same rules apply where the agent, renounces an agency for a fixed period.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Notice in this connection that want of skill, continuous disobedience of lawful orders, and rude or insulting behavior has been held to be sufficient cause for dismissal of an agent.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Further, reasonable notice has to be given by one party to the other; otherwise, damage resulting from want of such notice, will have to be paid (s.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] 207, the revocation or renunciation of an agency may be made expressly or implicitly by conduct.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The termination does not take effect as regards the agent, till it becomes known to him and as regards third party, till the termination is known to them (s.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] When an agent's authority is terminated, it operates as a termination of subagent also (s.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This has become a more difficult area as states are not consistent on the nature of a partnership.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Some states opt for the partnership as no more than an aggregate of the natural persons who have joined the firm.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Others treat the partnership as a business entity and, like a corporation, vest the partnership with a separate legal personality.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Hence, for example, in English law a partner is the agent of the other partners, whereas in Scots law "a [partnership] is a legal person distinct from the partners of whom it is composed" and so a partner is the agent of the partnership *per se*.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This form of agency is inherent in the status of a partner and does not arise out of a contract of agency with a principal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The Partnership Act 1890 of the United Kingdom (which includes both England and Scotland) provides that a partner who acts within the scope of his actual authority (express or implied) will bind the partnership when he does anything in the ordinary course of carrying on partnership business.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Even if that implied authority has been revoked or limited, the partner will have apparent authority unless the third party knows that the authority has been compromised.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Hence, if the partnership wishes to limit any partner's authority, it must give express notice of the limitation to the world.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] However, there would be little substantive difference if English law was amended: partners will bind the partnership rather than their fellow partners individually.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] For these purposes, the knowledge of the partner acting will be imputed to the other partners, or to the firm if a separate personality.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The other partners or the firm are the principal and third parties are entitled to assume that the principal has been informed of all relevant information.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This causes problems when one partner acts fraudulently or negligently and causes loss to clients of the firm.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In most states, a distinction is drawn between knowledge of the firm's general business activities and the confidential affairs as they affect one client.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Thus, there is no imputation if the partner is acting against the interests of the firm as a fraud.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] There is more likely to be liability in tort if the partnership benefited by receiving fee income for the work negligently performed, even if only as an aspect of the standard provisions of vicarious liability.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Whether the injured party wishes to sue the partnership or the individual partners is usually a matter for the plaintiff since, in most jurisdictions, their liability is joint and several.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Agency relationships are common in many professional areas.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An *agent* in commercial law (also referred to as a *manager*) is a person who is authorized to act on behalf of another (called the *principal* or *client*) to create a legal relationship with a third party.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] A legal entity may also act as an agent: For example, two corporate groups may assign the task of intermediating an M&A transaction to a business agency, that acts as a 3rd party, in order to finalize the deal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] This happens for example when you move over an entity to an intermediary holding company, before settling it into its final destination entity.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Real estate transactions refer to real estate brokerage, and mortgage brokerage.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In real estate brokerage, the buyers or sellers are the principals themselves and the broker or his salesperson who represents each principal is his agent.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In 1986, the European Communities enacted **Directive 86/653/EEC** on self-employed commercial agents.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Agency law in the United Kingdom is a component of UK commercial law, and forms a core set of rules necessary for the smooth functioning of business.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Agency law is primarily governed by the Common law and to a lesser extent by statutory instruments.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In the UK, the EEC Directive on self-employed commercial agents was transposed into national law in the Commercial Agents Regulations 1993.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Thus, agent and principals in a commercial agency relationship are subject both to the Common law and the Commercial Agents Regulations.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] The Commercial Agents Regulations require agents to act "dutifully and in good faith" in performing their activities (Reg.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] 3); co-extensively, principals are required principals to act "dutifully and in good faith" in their "relations" with their commercial agents (Reg 4).
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Although there is no statutory definition of this obligation to act "dutifully and in good faith", it has been suggested that it requires principals and agents to act "with honesty, openness and regard for the interests of the other party to the transaction".
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] "Firstly, expressing honesty and openness, commercial agents and principals must mutually co-operate in the performance of their agreement.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Conduct in good faith requires that each party proactively take action to assist the other in the realisation of their bargain, as opposed to mere abstention from obstructive behaviour.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] However, whether a party has acted in good faith must not be determined by reference to a moral or metaphysical notion of co-operation; this assessment must be based on an objective appraisal of the actual commercial agency relationship.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Accordingly, the intensity of the required co-operation will vary, depending on the terms of the contract and the pertinent commercial practices.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Secondly, commercial agents and principals must not exploit asymmetries in their agency relationship in such a manner that frustrates the legitimate expectations of the other party.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Nevertheless, the starting axiom of this investigation must be that these are commercial relationships in which professionals are expected to be self-reliant and must be free to pursue their self-interest.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Critically, this will not be an estimation aimed at achieving ontological fairness, a just bargain or equilibrium between the giving and receiving of commercial agents and principals".
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In Ireland, Directive 86/653/EEC was implemented in the Commercial Agents Regulations of 1994 and 1997.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In India, for the purposes of contractual law, section 182 of the Contract Act 1872 defines an agent as "a person employed to do any act for another or to represent another in dealings with third persons".
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] According to section 184, as between the principal and third persons, any person (whether he has contractual capacity or not) may become an agent.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] Thus, a minor or a person of unsound mind can also become an agent.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] An allograph may be the opposite of an autograph – i.e. a person's words or name (signature) written by someone else.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In law, an allograph is a writing or signature made by an agent on behalf of a principal.
[src:board-of-directors/agency-law] In American law, checks written by an agent of behalf of, and with the authority of, a principal are allographs for that principal.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A **board of directors** is a governing body that supervises the activities of a business, a nonprofit organization, or a government agency.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The powers, duties, and responsibilities of a board of directors are determined by government regulations (including the jurisdiction's corporate law) and the organization's own constitution and by-laws.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These authorities may specify the number of members of the board, how they are to be chosen, and how often they are to meet.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In an organization with voting members, the board is accountable to, and may be subordinate to, the organization's full membership, which usually elect the members of the board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In a stock corporation, non-executive directors are elected by the shareholders, and the board has ultimate responsibility for the management of the corporation.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In nations with codetermination (such as Germany and Sweden), the workers of a corporation elect a set fraction of the board's members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The board of directors appoints the chief executive officer of the corporation and sets out the overall strategic direction.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In corporations with dispersed ownership, the identification and nomination of directors (that shareholders vote for or against) are often done by the board itself, leading to a high degree of self-perpetuation.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In a non-stock corporation with no general voting membership, the board is the supreme governing body of the institution, and its members are sometimes chosen by the board itself.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Other names include *board of directors and advisors*, *board of governors*, *board of managers*, *board of regents*, *board of trustees*, and *board of visitors*.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It may also be called the *executive board*.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The legal responsibilities of boards and board members vary with the nature of the organization, and between jurisdictions.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] For companies with shares publicly listed for negotiation, these responsibilities are typically much more rigorous and complex than for those of other types.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Typically, the board chooses one of its members to be the *chairman* (often now called the "chair" or "chairperson"), who holds whatever title is specified in the by-laws or articles of association.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, in membership organizations, the members elect the president of the organization and the president becomes the board chair, unless the by-laws say otherwise.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The directors of an organization are the persons who are members of its board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Several specific terms categorize directors by the presence or absence of their other relationships to the organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Corporations may designate a former senior executive and ex-board member as an honorary board member, a position that does not carry any executive authority but represents recognition of the person's corporate governorship and performance.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] An inside director is a director who is also an employee, officer, chief executive, major shareholder, or someone similarly connected to the organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Inside directors represent the interests of the entity's stakeholders, and often have special knowledge of its inner workings, its financial or market position, and so on.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] An inside director who is employed as a manager or executive of the organization is sometimes referred to as an executive director (not to be confused with the title executive director sometimes used for the CEO position in some organizations).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Executive directors often have a specified area of responsibility in the organization, such as finance, marketing, human resources, or production.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] An outside director is a member of the board who is not otherwise employed by or engaged with the organization, and does not represent any of its stakeholders.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A typical example is a director who is president of a firm in a different industry.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Outside directors are not employees of the company or affiliated with it in any other way.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Outside directors bring outside experience and perspectives to the board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] For example, for a company that serves a domestic market only, the presence of CEOs from global multinational corporations as outside directors can help to provide insights on export and import opportunities and international trade options.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] One of the arguments for having outside directors is that they can keep a watchful eye on the inside directors and on the way the organization is run.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Outside directors are unlikely to tolerate "insider dealing" between inside directors, as outside directors do not benefit from the company or organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Outside directors are often useful in handling disputes between inside directors, or between shareholders and the board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] They are thought to be advantageous because they can be objective and present little risk of conflict of interest.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] On the other hand, they might lack familiarity with the specific issues connected to the organization's governance, and they might not know about the industry or sector in which the organization is operating.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Individual directors often serve on more than one board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This practice results in an interlocking directorate, where a relatively small number of individuals have significant influence over many important entities.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This situation can have important corporate, social, economic, and legal consequences, and has been the subject of significant research.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The science of this process has been slow to develop due to the secretive nature of the way most companies run their boards, however some standardization is beginning to develop.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Some who are pushing for this standardization in the US are the National Association of Corporate Directors, McKinsey and The Board Group.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A board of directors conducts its meetings according to the rules and procedures contained in its governing documents.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These procedures may allow the board to conduct its business by conference call or other electronic means.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] They may also specify how a quorum is to be determined.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The responsibilities of a board of directors vary depending on the nature and type of business entity and the laws applying to the entity (see types of business entity).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] There are numerous types of business entities available throughout the world such as a corporation, limited liability company, cooperative, business trust, partnership, private limited company, and public limited company.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Much of what has been written about boards of directors relates to boards of directors of business entities actively traded on public markets.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] More recently, however, material is becoming available for boards of private and closely held businesses including family businesses.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A board-only organization is one whose board is self-appointed, rather than being accountable to a base of members through elections; or in which the powers of the membership are extremely limited.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The amount of powers and authority delegated to the board depend on the bylaws and rules of the particular organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Some organizations place matters exclusively in the board's control while in others, the general membership retains full power and the board can only make recommendations.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The setup of a board of directors varies widely across organizations and may include provisions that are applicable to corporations, in which the "shareholders" are the members of the organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A difference may be that the membership elects the officers of the organization, such as the president and the secretary, and the officers become members of the board in addition to the directors and retain those duties on the board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The directors may also be classified as officers in this situation.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] There may also be ex-officio members of the board, or persons who are members due to another position that they hold.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These ex-officio members have all the same rights as the other board members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Members of the board may be removed before their term is complete.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Details on how they can be removed are usually provided in the bylaws.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] If the bylaws do not contain such details, the section on disciplinary procedures in *Robert's Rules of Order* may be used.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In a publicly held company, directors are elected to represent and are legally obligated as fiduciaries to represent owners of the company—the shareholders/stockholders.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In this capacity they establish policies and make decisions on issues such as whether there is a dividend and how much it is, stock options distributed to employees, and the hiring/firing and compensation of upper management.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Theoretically, the control of a company is divided between two bodies: the board of directors, and the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In practice, the amount of power exercised by the board varies with the type of company.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In small private companies, the directors and the shareholders are normally the same people, and thus there is no real division of power.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Another feature of boards of directors in large public companies is that the board tends to have more *de facto* power.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Most shareholders do not attend shareholder meetings, but rather cast proxy votes via mail, phone, or internet, thus allowing the board to vote for them.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, proxy votes are not a total delegation of the voting power, as the board must vote the proxy shares as directed by their owner even when it contradicts the board's views.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In addition, many shareholders vote to accept all recommendations of the board rather than try to get involved in management, since each shareholder's power, as well as interest and information is so small.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Larger institutional investors also grant the board proxies.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The large number of shareholders also makes it hard for them to organize.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, there have been moves recently to try to increase shareholder activism among both institutional investors and individuals with small shareholdings.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A contrasting view is that in large public companies it is upper management and not boards that wield practical power, because boards delegate nearly all of their power to the top executive employees, adopting their recommendations almost without fail.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] As a practical matter, executives even choose the directors, with shareholders normally following management recommendations and voting for them.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In most cases, serving on a board is not a career unto itself.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] For major corporations, the board members are usually professionals or leaders in their field.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In the case of outside directors, they are often senior leaders of other organizations.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Nevertheless, board members often receive remunerations amounting to hundreds of thousands of dollars per year since they often sit on the boards of several companies.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Inside directors are usually not paid for sitting on a board, but the duty is instead considered part of their larger job description.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Outside directors are usually paid for their services.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These remunerations vary between corporations, but usually consist of a yearly or monthly salary, additional compensation for each meeting attended, stock options, and various other benefits. such as travel, hotel and meal expenses for the board meetings.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Academic research has identified different types of board directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Their characteristics and experiences shape their role and performance.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] For instance, directors with multiple mandates are often referred to as busy directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Their monitoring performance is considered to be comparatively weak due to the limited time they can dedicate to this task.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Overconfident directors are found to pay higher premiums in corporate acquisitions and make worse takeover choices.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Locally rooted directors tend to be overrepresented and lack international experience, which can lead to lower valuations, especially in internationally oriented firms.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors' military experience is associated with rigorous monitoring and improved corporate governance.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In some European and Asian countries, there are two separate boards, an executive board (or management board) for day-to-day business and a supervisory board (elected by the shareholders and employees) for supervising the executive board.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In these countries, the chairman of the supervisory board is equivalent to the chairman of a single-tier board, while the chairman of the management board is reckoned as the company's CEO or managing director.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These two roles are always held by different people.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board and allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] There is a strong parallel here with the structure of government, where parliament (the supervisory board) oversees a cabinet of ministers (management officials, comprising the executive board) led by a head of government (CEO).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Board structures and procedures vary both within and among OECD countries.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Some countries have two-tier boards that separate the supervisory function and the management function into different bodies.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Such systems typically have a "supervisory board" composed of nonexecutive board members and a "management board" composed entirely of executives.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Other countries have "unitary" boards, which bring together executive and non-executive board members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In some countries there is also an additional statutory body for audit purposes.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The OECD Principles are intended to be sufficiently general to apply to whatever board structure is charged with the functions of governing the enterprise and monitoring management.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The development of a separate board of directors to manage/govern/oversee a company has occurred incrementally and indefinitely over legal history.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Until the end of the 19th century, it seems to have been generally assumed that the general meeting (of all shareholders) was the supreme organ of a company, and that the board of directors merely acted as an agent of the company subject to the control of the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The new approach did not secure immediate approval, but it was endorsed by the House of Lords in *Quin & Axtens v Salmon* [1909] AC 442 and has since received general acceptance.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Under English law, successive versions of Table A have reinforced the norm that, unless the directors are acting contrary to the law or the provisions of the Articles, the powers of conducting the management and affairs of the company are vested in them.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It has been remarked that this development in the law was somewhat surprising at the time, as the relevant provisions in Table A (as it was then) seemed to contradict this approach rather than to endorse it.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The age of board members has become a notable trend across global stock exchanges, reflecting an increasingly older demographic in leadership roles.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] As of 2025, the average age of board members of companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange stands at 62.2 years, while the United Kingdom reports an average of 60.1 years, Germany 59.3 years, South Korea 59 years, and Hong Kong 54.9 years.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] New York Stock Exchange companies exhibit the highest average age, at 62.9 years.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In response to this aging trend, some firms, particularly those in entertainment and trend-driven sectors, have actively sought to appoint younger board members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] An example is Sanrio, the Japanese company behind the Hello Kitty franchise, which reduced the average age of its board from 68 years in 2020 to 51 years by 2024, signaling a deliberate intergenerational shift in governance.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In most legal systems, the appointment and removal of directors is voted upon by the shareholders in general meeting or through a proxy statement.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] For publicly traded companies in the U.S., the directors which are available to vote on are largely selected by either the board as a whole or a nominating committee.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Shareholder nominations can only occur at the general meeting itself or through the prohibitively expensive process of mailing out ballots separately; in May 2009 the SEC proposed a new rule allowing shareholders meeting certain criteria to add nominees to the proxy statement.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In countries with co-determination, a fixed fraction of the board is elected by the corporation's workers.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors may also leave office by resignation or death.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In some legal systems, directors may also be removed by a resolution of the remaining directors (in some countries they may only do so "with cause"; in others the power is unrestricted).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Some jurisdictions also permit the board of directors to appoint directors, either to fill a vacancy which arises on resignation or death, or as an addition to the existing directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In practice, it can be quite difficult to remove a director by a resolution in general meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In many legal systems, the director has a right to receive special notice of any resolution to remove them; the company must often supply a copy of the proposal to the director, who is usually entitled to be heard by the meeting.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The director may require the company to circulate any representations that they wish to make.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Furthermore, the director's contract of service will usually entitle them to compensation if they are removed, and may often include a generous "golden parachute" which also acts as a deterrent to removal.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A 2010 study examined how corporate shareholders voted in director elections in the United States.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It found that directors received fewer votes from shareholders when their companies performed poorly, had excess CEO compensation, or had poor shareholder protection.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Also, directors received fewer votes when they did not regularly attend board meetings or received negative recommendations from a proxy advisory firm.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The study also shows that companies often improve their corporate governance by removing poison pills or classified boards and by reducing excessive CEO pay after their directors receive low shareholder support.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Board accountability to shareholders is a recurring issue.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In September 2010, *The New York Times* noted that several directors who had overseen companies which had failed in the 2008 financial crisis had found new positions as directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The SEC sometimes imposes a ban (a "D&O bar") on serving on a board as part of its fraud cases, and one of these was upheld in 2013.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The exercise by the board of directors of its powers usually occurs in board meetings.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Most legal systems require sufficient notice to be given to all directors of these meetings, and that a quorum must be present before any business may be conducted.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In most common law countries, the powers of the board are vested in the board as a whole, and not in the individual directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, in instances an individual director may still bind the company by their acts by virtue of their ostensible authority (see also: the rule in *Turquand's Case*).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Because directors exercise control and management over the organization, but organizations are (in theory) run for the benefit of the shareholders, the law imposes strict duties on directors in relation to the exercise of their duties.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The duties imposed on directors are fiduciary duties, similar to those that the law imposes on those in similar positions of trust: agents and trustees.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The duties apply to each director separately, while the powers apply to the board jointly.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Also, the duties are owed to the company itself, and not to any other entity.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This does not mean that directors can never stand in a fiduciary relationship to the individual shareholders; they may well have such a duty in certain circumstances.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors must exercise their powers for a proper purpose.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] While in many instances an improper purpose is readily evident, such as a director looking to enrich themselves or divert an investment opportunity to a relative, such breaches usually involve a breach of the director's duty to act in good faith.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Greater difficulties arise where the director, while acting in good faith, is serving a purpose that is not regarded by the law as proper.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The seminal authority in the United Kingdom in relation to what amounts to a proper purpose is the Supreme Court decision in Eclairs Group Ltd v JKX Oil & Gas plc (2015).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The case concerned the powers of directors under the articles of association of the company to disenfranchise voting rights attached to shares for failure to properly comply with notice served on the shareholders.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Prior to that case the leading authority was *Howard Smith Ltd v Ampol Ltd* [1974] AC 821.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The case concerned the power of the directors to issue new shares.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It was alleged that the directors had issued many new shares purely to deprive a particular shareholder of his voting majority.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] If so, the mere fact that an incidental result (even if it was a desired consequence) was that a shareholder lost their majority, or a takeover bid was defeated, this would not itself make the share issue improper.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] But if the sole purpose was to destroy a voting majority, or block a takeover bid, that would be an improper purpose.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Not all jurisdictions recognised the "proper purpose" duty as separate from the "good faith" duty however.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors cannot, without the consent of the company, fetter their discretion in relation to the exercise of their powers, and cannot bind themselves to vote in a particular way at future board meetings.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This is so even if there is no improper motive or purpose, and no personal advantage to the director.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This does not mean, however, that the board cannot agree to the company entering into a contract which binds the company to a certain course, even if certain actions in that course will require further board approval, such as issuing bonds.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The company remains bound, but the directors retain the discretion to vote against taking the future actions (although that may involve a breach by the company of the contract that the board previously approved).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] As fiduciaries, the directors may not put themselves in a position where their interests and duties conflict with the duties that they owe to the company.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The law takes the view that good faith must not only be done, but must be manifestly seen to be done, and zealously patrols the conduct of directors in this regard; and will not allow directors to escape liability by asserting that their decisions were in fact well founded.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] By definition, where a director enters into a transaction with a company, there is a conflict between the director's interest (to enrich themselves with the transaction) and their duty to the company (to ensure that the company gets as much as it can out of the transaction).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In some places, this rule is so strictly enforced that, even where the conflict of interest or conflict of duty is purely hypothetical, the directors can be forced to disgorge all personal gains arising from it.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] "A corporate body can only act by agents, and it is, of course, the duty of those agents so to act as best to promote the interests of the corporation whose affairs they are conducting.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Such agents have duties to discharge of a fiduciary nature towards their principal.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] , with the interests of those whom he is bound to protect...
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, in many jurisdictions the members of the company are permitted to ratify transactions which would otherwise fall foul of this principle.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It is also largely accepted in most jurisdictions that this principle can be overridden in the company's constitution.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] In many countries, there is also a statutory duty to declare interests in relation to any transactions, and the director can be fined for failing to make disclosure.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors must not, without the informed consent of the company, use for their own profit the company's assets, opportunities, or information.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This prohibition is much less flexible than the prohibition against the transactions with the company, and attempts to circumvent it using provisions in the articles have met with limited success.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] And accordingly, the directors were required to disgorge the profits that they made, and the shareholders received their windfall.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The decision has been followed in several subsequent cases, and is now regarded as settled law.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors cannot compete directly with the company without a conflict of interest arising.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Similarly, they should not act as directors of competing companies, as their duties to each company would then conflict with each other.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Traditionally, the level of care and skill which has to be demonstrated by a director has been framed largely with reference to the non-executive director.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, a more modern approach has since developed, and in *Dorchester Finance Co Ltd v Stebbing* [1989] BCLC 498 the court held that the rule in *Equitable Fire* related only to skill, and not to diligence.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This was a dual subjective and objective test, and one deliberately pitched at a higher level.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] More recently, it has been suggested that both the tests of skill and diligence should be assessed objectively and subjectively; in the United Kingdom, the statutory provisions relating to directors' duties in the new Companies Act 2006 have been codified on this basis.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Historically, directors' duties have been owed almost exclusively to the company and its members, and the board was expected to exercise its powers for the financial benefit of the company.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] However, more recently there have been attempts to "soften" the position, and provide for more scope for directors to act as good corporate citizens.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This represents a considerable departure from the traditional notion that directors' duties are owed only to the company.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The changes have therefore been the subject of some criticism.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The adoption of technology that facilitates the meeting preparation and execution of directors continues to grow.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Board directors are increasingly leveraging this technology to communicate and collaborate within a secure environment to access meeting materials, communicate with each other, and execute their governance responsibilities.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This trend is particularly acute in the United States where a robust market of early adopters garnered acceptance of board software by organizations resulting in higher penetration of the board portal services in the region.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Most companies have weak mechanisms for bringing the voice of society into the board room.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] They rely on personalities who were not appointed for their understanding of societal issues.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Often they give limited focus (both through time and financial resource) to issues of corporate responsibility and sustainability.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A social board has society designed into its structure.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] It elevates the voice of society through specialist appointments to the board and mechanisms that empower innovation from within the organisation.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Social boards align themselves with themes that are important to society.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] These may include measuring worker pay ratios, linking personal social and environmental objectives to remuneration, integrated reporting, fair tax and B-Corp certification.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Social boards recognise that they are part of society and that they require more than a licence to operate to succeed.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] They balance short-term shareholder pressure against long-term value creation, managing the business for a plurality of stakeholders including employees, shareholders, supply chains and civil society.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] India has no legislative equivalent to Sarbanes–Oxley Act (given below), though Clause 49 of the SEBI Listing Agreement provides relevant rules.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] India adopted this new corporate governance standard under Article 49 of the Listing Agreement on 31 December 2005, which is mandatory for all listed companies.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] This provision mandates certain governance practices for companies listed on Indian stock exchanges.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Key provisions under clause 49 include those under which top executives like CEOs and CFOs must verify the effectiveness and accuracy of financial statements.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] After the Satyam scandal in 2009, internal financial controls gained importance in India.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The Companies Act, 2013 introduced internal financial controls imposing specific responsibilities on the board, audit committee, management and others.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002 has introduced new standards of accountability on boards of U.S. companies or companies listed on U.S. stock exchanges.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Under the act, directors risk large fines and prison sentences in the case of accounting crimes.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Internal control is now the direct responsibility of directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The vast majority of companies covered by the act have hired internal auditors to ensure that the company adheres to required standards of internal control.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The internal auditors are required by law to report directly to an audit board, consisting of directors more than half of whom are outside directors, one of whom is a "financial expert".
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The law requires companies listed on the major stock exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ) to have a majority of independent directors—directors who are not otherwise employed by the firm or in a business relationship with it.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] According to the Corporate Library's study, the average size of publicly traded company's board is 9.2 members, and most boards range from 3 to 31 members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] According to Investopedia, some analysts think the ideal size is seven.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] State law may specify a minimum number of directors, maximum number of directors, and qualifications for directors (e.g. whether board members must be individuals or may be business entities).
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] While a board may have several committees, two—the compensation committee and audit committee—are critical and must be made up of at least three independent directors and no inside directors.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Other common committees in boards are nominating, governance and investment.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Directors of Fortune 500 companies received median pay of $234,000 in 2011.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A 2011 study by the National Association of Corporate Directors in the United States estimated that directors averaged 4.3 hours a week on board work.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Surveys have indicated that about 20% of nonprofit foundations pay their board members, and 2% of American nonprofit organizations do.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] 80% of nonprofit organizations require board members to personally contribute to the organization.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] As of 2007, this percentage had increased in recent years.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] According to John Gillespie, a former investment banker and co-author of a book critical of boards, "Far too much of their time has been for check-the-box and cover-your-behind activities rather than real monitoring of executives and providing strategic advice on behalf of shareholders".
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] At the same time, scholars have found that individual directors have a large effect on major corporate initiatives such as mergers and acquisitions and cross-border investments.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] According to the International Institute of Management, the rise in investor dissatisfaction, class-action lawsuits and shareholder activism has resulted in more attention directed toward the board of directors and the lack of corporate governance accountability.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Shareholders' complaints include issues such as excessive executive compensation and passive participation (lack of proper governance) of the board members.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The journal paper cites examples of underperforming CEOs of Fortune 500 companies who took compensation and retirement package in hundreds of millions of dollars while the stock price of their companies lost billions of dollars.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The research proposes institutionalizing a standardized board evaluation framework to help balance between the executive compensation and protecting the interest of shareholders.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] The issue of gender representation on corporate boards of directors has been the subject of much criticism in recent years.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] Governments and corporations have responded with measures such as legislation mandating gender quotas and comply or explain systems to address the disproportionality of gender representation on corporate boards.
[src:board-of-directors/board-of-directors] A study of the French corporate elite has found that certain social classes are also disproportionately represented on boards, with those from the upper and, especially, upper-middle classes tending to dominate.
